anizations. Thus, it argues that change in military organizations requires "incubators," designated subunits established outside the normal bureaucratic hierarchy, and "advocacy networks" championing new concepts. Incubators, ranging from special study groups to non-Title 10 war games and field exercises, provide a safe space for experimentation and the construction of new operational concepts. Advocacy networks then connect different constituents and inject them with concepts developed in incubators. This injection makes changes elites would have otherwise rejected a contagious narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMilitary doctrinexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMilitary doctrinexHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aMilitary doctrinezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary doctrinezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aOrganizational changexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aOrganizational changexHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aOrganizational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrganizational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aU.S. Army. 4aactive defense. 4aadvocacy network. 4aairland battle. 4acounterinsurgency. 4afull-dimensional operations. 4aincubator. 4amilitary doctrine. 4amilitary innovation. 4aorganizational change. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479738240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797382423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797382.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles